    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \nabla }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/a3d0e93b78c50237f9ea83d027e4ebbdaef354b2" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.936ex; height:2.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \nabla }"></span>, written as an upside-down triangle and pronounced "del", denotes the <a href="/wiki/Del" title="Del">vector differential operator</a>.
</p><p>When a coordinate system is used in which the basis vectors are not functions of position, the gradient is given by the <a href="/wiki/Vector_(mathematics_and_physics)" title="Vector (mathematics and physics)">vector</a><sup id="cite_ref-row-column_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-row-column-2"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> whose components are the <a href="/wiki/Partial_derivative" title="Partial derivative">partial derivatives</a> of <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle f}">
