          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>θ<!-- θ --></mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mrow>
              <mi>r</mi>
              <mi>sin</mi>
              <mo>⁡<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
              <mi>θ<!-- θ --></mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant="normal">∂<!-- ∂ --></mi>
              <mi>f</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant="normal">∂<!-- ∂ --></mi>
              <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant="bold">e</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \nabla f(r,\theta ,\varphi )={\frac {\partial f}{\partial r}}\mathbf {e} _{r}+{\frac {1}{r}}{\frac {\partial f}{\partial \theta }}\mathbf {e} _{\theta }+{\frac {1}{r\sin \theta }}{\frac {\partial f}{\partial \varphi }}\mathbf {e} _{\varphi },}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/4b9a4289d5a458f0146919f8d793ac92ba5b7e62" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:46.28ex; height:6.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \nabla f(r,\theta ,\varphi )={\frac {\partial f}{\partial r}}\mathbf {e} _{r}+{\frac {1}{r}}{\frac {\partial f}{\partial \theta }}\mathbf {e} _{\theta }+{\frac {1}{r\sin \theta }}{\frac {\partial f}{\partial \varphi }}\mathbf {e} _{\varphi },}"></span>
</p><p>where <span class="texhtml"><i>r</i></span> is the radial distance, <span class="texhtml"><i>φ</i></span> is the azimuthal angle and <span class="texhtml"><i>θ</i></span> is the polar angle, and <span class="texhtml"><b>e</b><sub><i>r</i></sub></span>, <span class="texhtml"><b>e</b><sub><i>θ</i></sub></span> and <span class="texhtml"><b>e</b><sub><i>φ</i></sub></span> are again local unit vectors pointing in the coordinate directions (that is, the normalized <a href="/wiki/Curvilinear_coordinates#Covariant_and_contravariant_bases" title="Curvilinear coordinates">covariant basis</a>).
</p><p>For the gradient in other <a href="/wiki/Orthogonal_coordinate_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Orthogonal coordinate system">orthogonal coordinate systems</a>, see <a href="/wiki/Orthogonal_coordinates#Differential_operators_in_three_dimensions" title="Orthogonal coordinates">Orthogonal coordinates (Differential operators in three dimensions)</a>.
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="General_coordinates">General coordinates</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Gradient&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: General coordinates"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>We consider <a href="/wiki/Curvilinear_coordinates" title="Curvilinear coordinates">general coordinates</a>, which we write as <span class="texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>1</sup>, …, <i>x</i><sup><i>i</i></sup>, …, <i>x</i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span>, where <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">n</span> is the number of dimensions of the domain. Here, the upper index refers to the position in the list of the coordinate or component, so <span class="texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span> refers to the second component—not the quantity <span class="texhtml"><i>x</i></span> squared. The index variable <span class="texhtml"><i>i</i></span> refers to an arbitrary element <span class="texhtml"><i>x</i><sup><i>i</i></sup></span>. Using <a href="/wiki/Einstein_notation" title="Einstein notation">Einstein notation</a>, the gradient can then be written as:
</p><p><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \nabla f={\frac {\partial f}{\partial x^{i}}}g^{ij}\mathbf {e} _{j}}">
  <semantics>
