          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \nabla \mathbf {f} =g^{jk}{\frac {\partial f^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}}\mathbf {e} _{i}\otimes \mathbf {e} _{k},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/27bdc5c9d3fe5e1ec927fb93e5b05a8c9402a045" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.171ex; width:21.192ex; height:6.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \nabla \mathbf {f} =g^{jk}{\frac {\partial f^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}}\mathbf {e} _{i}\otimes \mathbf {e} _{k},}"></span>
</p><p>(where the <a href="/wiki/Einstein_summation_notation" class="mw-redirect" title="Einstein summation notation">Einstein summation notation</a> is used and the <a href="/wiki/Tensor_product" title="Tensor product">tensor product</a> of the vectors <span class="texhtml"><b>e</b><sub><i>i</i></sub></span> and <span class="texhtml"><b>e</b><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> is a <a href="/wiki/Dyadic_tensor" class="mw-redirect" title="Dyadic tensor">dyadic tensor</a> of type (2,0)). Overall, this expression equals the transpose of the Jacobian matrix:
</p><p><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle {\frac {\partial f^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}}={\frac {\partial (f^{1},f^{2},f^{3})}{\partial (x^{1},x^{2},x^{3})}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
